article.headline: Smith debuts for Shock after Saturday's trade
article.linkText: Shock storm back in second half to top Mercury
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock's worst loss
might've been just what they needed to turn their season around.

Kara Braxton scored 16 points and grabbed six rebounds, helping
the Shock overcome a 17-point, second-half deficit and beat the
Phoenix Mercury 66-63 on Sunday.

Following a 40-point loss to Sacramento on July 24, the Shock
fell four games under .500 and were slipping out of the playoff
picture in the Eastern Conference.

"The players realized that they really weren't giving all their
effort every game," said coach Bill Laimbeer, whose team has won
two straight. "They talked amongst themselves, and they came to
the conclusion that now is the time to stand up and see how good we
can be."

On Sunday, Detroit (10-12) didn't play its best game -- the Shock
committed 25 turnovers that led to 31 points -- but they did just
enough to hold off the Mercury.

"Turnovers are frying my brain," Laimbeer said. "It's so
difficult for a coach to sit there and watch it happen, but we
overcame it to our credit."

Anna DeForge had 20 points, and Diana Taurasi added 16 and seven
assists for Phoenix (10-13), which had 18 turnovers and was
outrebounded 38-19. It was the Mercury's second loss in nine games.

"You can't expect to win on the road when you don't rebound and
you don't take care of the ball," DeForge said.

Early in the second half, it looked like Phoenix was going to
cruise to an easy victory. But with the Mercury ahead 45-28,
Detroit started to chip away.

The Shock used a 10-0 run to cut the deficit to 45-38, and
following Penny Taylor's two free throws for Phoenix, they scored
seven straight points to get within two.

Detroit took a 51-50 lead after Braxton's jumper with 6:32 left,
and the Shock went up 61-55 with under three minutes left.

Phoenix made a late comeback attempt, getting within 64-63 after
two free throws by Taurasi with 8.7 seconds remaining. But Ruth
Riley sealed the victory with an offensive rebound and a pair of
free throws.

"We didn't execute at the end of the game and that was my
error," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said.

Deanna Nolan scored 12, and Riley finished with 10 points and
eight rebounds for the Shock. Katie Smith had six points and three
assists in her first game with Detroit after being traded from
Minnesota on Saturday.

Detroit sent Chandi Jones, Stacey Thomas and a 2006 first-round
pick to the Lynx for Smith, a five-time WNBA All-Star and the
league's career leader in 3-pointers made.

"This team has a lot of pieces and if we put them all together
we can make a nice run," said Smith, who has a career average of
more than 17 points per game. "I'm excited to have a chance to
help out a good team."
